column1: Will the UN Security Council adopt a resolution concerning the Democratic People's Republic of Korea between 7 September 2017 and 4 October 2017?
column6: ['Foreign Policy', 'Security and Conflict']
column11: The UN Security Council adopted a DPRK resolution. This question closed as "a) yes" with and end date of 11 September 2017. This question will resolve as "yes" if the United Nations Security Council (UNSC) adopts a resolution during the period of interest in which the country/region of interest appears in the short description in the Security Council Resolution table and/or is mentioned within the adopted resolution itself.

Any such resolution would have to pass muster with China and Russia. This means that the resolution would probably be weak, and not offer any effective solution to the problem of North Korean proliferation. I think the Trump administration would consider a weak resolution worse than no resolution, and will not settle for a compromise. China doesn't want to see any kind of economic hardship in North Korea which might send refugees into China, and I doubt if China approves of international organizations meddling in sovereign countries for any reason.

Kennedy ordered a complete blockade around the island to prevent Soviet missiles from being installed. The resolution calls for something far less comprehensive than a total blockade, which is widely considered an act of war. But it would authorize a committee of the Security Council to “designate vessels for nonconsensual inspections” and authorize all members of the United Nations — using military vessels and aircraft — “to inspect on the high seas any vessel designated by the committee.” Some resolution will be passed
